 him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Erskine was born in 1338, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Erskine, was 28 and his mother, Lady Beatrice de Lindsay, was 53. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Jean Cameron. He died in 1406, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1338–1406":"1338–1406","1328–1346":"1328–1346","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1344–1406":"1344–1406","1346–1403":"1346–1403","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1336–1402":"1336–1402","1362–1468":"1362–1468","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1285–1352":"1285–1352","1385":"1385","1352":"1352","1362":"1362","1285":"1285","1338":"1338","1349":"1349","1403":"1403","1402":"1402","1468":"1468","1336":"1336","1368":"1368","1346":"1346","1411":"1411","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","2 May 1352":"2. mai 1352","about 1368":"umbes 1368","1409":"1409","1406":"1406","1328":"1328","Kinnoull, Perthshire, Scotland":"Kinnoull, Perthshire, Scotland","Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Sanquhar, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kinnoul, Perthshire, Scotland":"Kinnoul, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1338–1406":"1338–1406","1328–1346":"1328–1346","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1344–1406":"1344–1406","1346–1403":"1346–1403","1349–Female":"1349–Kuollut","1336–1402":"1336–1402","1362–1468":"1362–1468","1368–1409":"1368–1409","1310–1385":"1310–1385","1285–1352":"1285–1352"